description.narrative:
A total of 38 HRDs (9 from all over our target regions, 22 from Belarus due to the unprecedented crisis (co-funded by German Marshall Fund and German Ministry of Foreign Affairs), and 7 from Kyrgyzstan due to a less unprecedented crisis that was co-funded by National Endowment for Democracy). It has to be mentioned that just at the end of the reporting period, we finalized the selection process for our new participants. 12 HRDs were selected - 4 from Kyrgyzstan, 3 from Russian Federation, 2 from Tajikistan, 2 from Ukraine, and 1 from Uzbekistan. 

Outputs stated in the project: 

    • Strengthened security of HRDs participating in the program through the development of comprehensive individually tailored security plans;
    • Decreased level of stress and vulnerability of HRDs as the result of psychological counseling and consultations - a total of 171 hours;
    • Improved network of international professional and media contacts of HRDs participants of the program; With our support, HRDs were able to secure funds from National Endowment for Democracy, Frontline Defenders, Protect Defenders, and OSI for their future projects. Furthermore, they are happy to be able to network with different local NGOs and media outlets in Georgia - BILIKI, OC Media, Women’s Informational Center, Human Rights House, Radio Liberty, and Tbilisi Pride.
The impact of the project is in sustained human rights activism in the Central Asia region, Russia (especially North Caucasus), Belarus, and Crimea achieved through increased resilience of human rights defenders and their strengthened capacity. The project improved the security of HRDs in the region as they know that in case of urgency they can be supported and relocated to safety, as well as enabled HRDs to perform their activity better after they receive professional psychological support. If before HRDs had to deal with their burnout, psychological or medical problems on their own, now they know that asking for help is normal and there is a place where such help can be provided. As a result, more HRDs are able to perform their work sustainably. This strengthens their work for others and improves the human rights situation in the region.
